    fxs:embedsAsset <https://interego-css.livelysky-8b81abb0.eastus.azurecontainerapps.io/markj/courses/lesson3/asset/story_content%2F5gtwDF7sBFF_44100_48_0.mp3> ;
    fxs:embedsAsset <https://interego-css.livelysky-8b81abb0.eastus.azurecontainerapps.io/markj/courses/lesson3/asset/story_content%2F6Rv8igKXCV7_44100_48_0.mp3> ;
    fxs:hasNarration <https://interego-css.livelysky-8b81abb0.eastus.azurecontainerapps.io/markj/courses/lesson3/narration/story_content%2F6Uhqd0AwLft_44100_48_0.mp3> ;
    fxs:hasNarration <https://interego-css.livelysky-8b81abb0.eastus.azurecontainerapps.io/markj/courses/lesson3/narration/story_content%2F5gtwDF7sBFF_44100_48_0.mp3> ;
    fxs:hasNarration <https://interego-css.livelysky-8b81abb0.eastus.azurecontainerapps.io/markj/courses/lesson3/narration/story_content%2F6Rv8igKXCV7_44100_48_0.mp3> ;
    fxs:extractedTextCorpus "More commonly used in bulk renewable generation inverters; more accurately produces controllable power output.; Image 43.emf; Reactive Power; Simpler and more easily used in distribution-connected DER.; Image 45.emf; Approach 2:  PPS controls dc voltage and the inverter manages active power.; Rectangle 6; Rectangle 9; Rectangle 1; Rectangle 7; Rectangle 5; Rectangle 4; Rectangle 10; Rectangle 2; Approach 1:  Primary power source (PPS) controls active power and the inverter controls Vdc.\\nApproach 2:  PPS controls dc voltage and the inverter manages active power.  ; Approach 1:  Primary power source (PPS) controls active power and the inverter controls Vdc.; Reactive power reference (Q*ppc) from the plant controller to the inverter; Rectangle 8; Active Power; Image 44.emf; Open Loop; Closed Loop; Rectangle 11; Image 42.emf" .

<https://interego-css.livelysky-8b81abb0.eastus.azurecontainerapps.io/markj/courses/lesson3/asset/story_content%2F6Uhqd0AwLft_44100_48_0.mp3> a fxs:Asset ;
    dcterms:format "audio/mpeg" ;
    fxs:fileLocator "package!/story_content/6Uhqd0AwLft_44100_48_0.mp3" ;
    schema:duration "PT36S"^^xsd:duration ;
    prov:wasDerivedFrom <https://interego-css.livelysky-8b81abb0.eastus.azurecontainerapps.io/markj/courses/lesson3> .

<https://interego-css.livelysky-8b81abb0.eastus.azurecontainerapps.io/markj/courses/lesson3/narration/story_content%2F6Uhqd0AwLft_44100_48_0.mp3> a fxs:NarrationTranscript ;
    dcterms:language "en" ;
    schema:duration "PT36S"^^xsd:duration ;
    cnt:chars "There are two common approaches for managing DC voltage so that the inverter's output voltage is synchronized with the grid. In one approach, the primary power source controls active power while the inverter regulates DC voltage. In the other approach, the source controls DC voltage and the inverter manages active power. We'll focus on the first approach. This approach is used, for example, in a maximum PPS tracking scheme where the maximum power is extracted from the primary power source. Click each button to learn how active and reactive power control systems are implemented." ;
    fxs:transcribedBy <https://github.com/SYSTRAN/faster-whisper#tiny.en> ;
    prov:wasDerivedFrom <https://interego-css.livelysky-8b81abb0.eastus.azurecontainerapps.io/markj/courses/lesson3/asset/story_content%2F6Uhqd0AwLft_44100_48_0.mp3> .

<https://interego-css.livelysky-8b81abb0.eastus.azurecontainerapps.io/markj/courses/lesson3/asset/story_content%2F5gtwDF7sBFF_44100_48_0.mp3> a fxs:Asset ;
    dcterms:format "audio/mpeg" ;
    fxs:fileLocator "package!/story_content/5gtwDF7sBFF_44100_48_0.mp3" ;
    schema:duration "PT27S"^^xsd:duration ;
    prov:wasDerivedFrom <https://interego-css.livelysky-8b81abb0.eastus.azurecontainerapps.io/markj/courses/lesson3> .

<https://interego-css.livelysky-8b81abb0.eastus.azurecontainerapps.io/markj/courses/lesson3/narration/story_content%2F5gtwDF7sBFF_44100_48_0.mp3> a fxs:NarrationTranscript ;
    dcterms:language "en" ;
    schema:duration "PT27S"^^xsd:duration ;
    cnt:chars "Reactive power can be controlled in open loop or closed loop. With open loop control, the reference set point for reactive current is determined based on the reactive power set point and the voltage measurement. So Q, reactive power divided by Vd, voltage gives the reactive reference current. With closed loop control, the reference reactive power is compared to the measured reactive power and then a compensator generates the reactive reference current." ;
    fxs:transcribedBy <https://github.com/SYSTRAN/faster-whisper#tiny.en> ;
    prov:wasDerivedFrom <https://interego-css.livelysky-8b81abb0.eastus.azurecontainerapps.io/markj/courses/lesson3/asset/story_content%2F5gtwDF7sBFF_44100_48_0.mp3> .

<https://interego-css.livelysky-8b81abb0.eastus.azurecontainerapps.io/markj/courses/lesson3/asset/story_content%2F6Rv8igKXCV7_44100_48_0.mp3> a fxs:Asset ;
    dcterms:format "audio/mpeg" ;
    fxs:fileLocator "package!/story_content/6Rv8igKXCV7_44100_48_0.mp3" ;
    schema:duration "PT46S"^^xsd:duration ;
    prov:wasDerivedFrom <https://interego-css.livelysky-8b81abb0.eastus.azurecontainerapps.io/markj/courses/lesson3> .

<https://interego-css.livelysky-8b81abb0.eastus.azurecontainerapps.io/markj/courses/lesson3/narration/story_content%2F6Rv8igKXCV7_44100_48_0.mp3> a fxs:NarrationTranscript ;
    dcterms:language "en" ;
    schema:duration "PT46S"^^xsd:duration ;
    cnt:chars "Let's examine two DC control approaches used to determine the amount of active power. In the first approach, control is based on DC-voltage squared control, where VDC squared control develops an active power reference. This reference can then be used for either closed loop active power control or open loop control by calculating a current reference. This approach is more commonly used in bulk renewable generation inverters and more accurately produces controllable power output. The second DC voltage control approach controls VDC directly by developing the current reference to maintain the desired voltage level. This approach is more easily used in distribution-connected distributed energy resources or DER." ;
    fxs:transcribedBy <https://github.com/SYSTRAN/faster-whisper#tiny.en> ;
    prov:wasDerivedFrom <https://interego-css.livelysky-8b81abb0.eastus.azurecontainerapps.io/markj/courses/lesson3/asset/story_content%2F6Rv8igKXCV7_44100_48_0.mp3> .

<https://interego-css.livelysky-8b81abb0.eastus.azurecontainerapps.io/markj/courses/lesson3/slide/6cuGuY88hng> a fxs:Slide ;
    dcterms:title "Voltage Control" ;
    fxs:identifiedBy "6cuGuY88hng" ;
    fxs:sequenceIndex 6 ;
    fxs:fileLocator "package!/html5/data/js/6cuGuY88hng.js" ;
    prov:wasDerivedFrom <https://interego-css.livelysky-8b81abb0.eastus.azurecontainerapps.io/markj/courses/lesson3/res/__69JeglEuzyv_RES> ;
    schema:identifier "Slide7" ;
    fxs:embedsAsset <https://interego-css.livelysky-8b81abb0.eastus.azurecontainerapps.io/markj/courses/lesson3/asset/story_content%2F6JiqSURUYvI_44100_48_0.mp3> ;
    fxs:embedsAsset <https://interego-css.livelysky-8b81abb0.eastus.azurecontainerapps.io/markj/courses/lesson3/asset/story_content%2F5ZIVqtC2X4g_44100_48_0.mp3> ;
    fxs:embedsAsset <https://interego-css.livelysky-8b81abb0.eastus.azurecontainerapps.io/markj/courses/lesson3/asset/story_content%2F6I0VR61PQcO_44100_48_0.mp3> ;
    fxs:embedsAsset <https://interego-css.livelysky-8b81abb0.eastus.azurecontainerapps.io/markj/courses/lesson3/asset/story_content%2F5jMp1uOBvcw_44100_48_0.mp3> ;
    fxs:embedsAsset <https://interego-css.livelysky-8b81abb0.eastus.azurecontainerapps.io/markj/courses/lesson3/asset/story_content%2F6SypeIXvavu_44100_48_0.mp3> ;
    fxs:embedsAsset <https://interego-css.livelysky-8b81abb0.eastus.azurecontainerapps.io/markj/courses/lesson3/asset/story_content%2F5nckAIutyat_44100_48_0.mp3> ;
    fxs:hasNarration <https://interego-css.livelysky-8b81abb0.eastus.azurecontainerapps.io/markj/courses/lesson3/narration/story_content%2F6JiqSURUYvI_44100_48_0.mp3> ;
    fxs:hasNarration <https://interego-css.livelysky-8b81abb0.eastus.azurecontainerapps.io/markj/courses/lesson3/narration/story_content%2F5ZIVqtC2X4g_44100_48_0.mp3> ;
    fxs:hasNarration <https://interego-css.livelysky-8b81abb0.eastus.azurecontainerapps.io/markj/courses/lesson3/narration/story_content%2F6I0VR61PQcO_44100_48_0.mp3> ;
    fxs:hasNarration <https://interego-css.livelysky-8b81abb0.eastus.azurecontainerapps.io/markj/courses/lesson3/narration/story_content%2F5jMp1uOBvcw_44100_48_0.mp3> ;
    fxs:hasNarration <https://interego-css.livelysky-8b81abb0.eastus.azurecontainerapps.io/markj/courses/lesson3/narration/story_content%2F6SypeIXvavu_44100_48_0.mp3> ;
    fxs:hasNarration <https://interego-css.livelysky-8b81abb0.eastus.azurecontainerapps.io/markj/courses/lesson3/narration/story_content%2F5nckAIutyat_44100_48_0.mp3> ;
    fxs:extractedTextCorpus "Required to account for voltage drops due to changing frequency. \\nNote:  Lg may take on a range of values based on system conditions.; Grid strength at connection point; IBR Internal control system; Image 48.png; Vgd - System Voltage; It is common to limit recovery rate of id1\\nNote: Lg may take on a range of values based on system conditions.; voltage drop across the system inductance due to the rotating reference frame; Rectangle 17; For transmission, assume impedance (X)>> resistance (R)\\nControl terminal voltage (Vtd1) controlled by reactive current (iq1); Note: Lg may take on a range of values based on system conditions.; Rectangle 6; Rectangle 9; represents voltage drop due to system inductance and the rate of change of the active current; Rectangle 1; Image 52.emf; Image 50.emf; IBR response is dependent on:; Rectangle 7; Rectangle 12; Control terminal voltage (Vtd1) controlled by reactive current (iq1); Rectangle 3; Rectangle 5; Rectangle 4; It is common to limit recovery rate" .

<https://interego-css.livelysky-8b81abb0.eastus.azurecontainerapps.io/markj/courses/lesson3/asset/story_content%2F6JiqSURUYvI_44100_48_0.mp3> a fxs:Asset ;
    dcterms:format "audio/mpeg" ;
    fxs:fileLocator "package!/story_content/6JiqSURUYvI_44100_48_0.mp3" ;
    schema:duration "PT15S"^^xsd:duration ;
    prov:wasDerivedFrom <https://interego-css.livelysky-8b81abb0.eastus.azurecontainerapps.io/markj/courses/lesson3> .

<https://interego-css.livelysky-8b81abb0.eastus.azurecontainerapps.io/markj/courses/lesson3/narration/story_content%2F6JiqSURUYvI_44100_48_0.mp3> a fxs:NarrationTranscript ;
    dcterms:language "en" ;
    schema:duration "PT15S"^^xsd:duration ;
    cnt:chars "As you learned earlier, terminal voltage is dependent on both the inverter and how the system is reacting to it. We assume that the inverter autonomously measures and regulates terminal voltage locally without receiving a voltage reference point from the plant controller." ;
    fxs:transcribedBy <https://github.com/SYSTRAN/faster-whisper#tiny.en> ;
    prov:wasDerivedFrom <https://interego-css.livelysky-8b81abb0.eastus.azurecontainerapps.io/markj/courses/lesson3/asset/story_content%2F6JiqSURUYvI_44100_48_0.mp3> .

<https://interego-css.livelysky-8b81abb0.eastus.azurecontainerapps.io/markj/courses/lesson3/asset/story_content%2F5ZIVqtC2X4g_44100_48_0.mp3> a fxs:Asset ;
    dcterms:format "audio/mpeg" ;
    fxs:fileLocator "package!/story_content/5ZIVqtC2X4g_44100_48_0.mp3" ;
    schema:duration "PT39S"^^xsd:duration ;
    prov:wasDerivedFrom <https://interego-css.livelysky-8b81abb0.eastus.azurecontainerapps.io/markj/courses/lesson3> .

<https://interego-css.livelysky-8b81abb0.eastus.azurecontainerapps.io/markj/courses/lesson3/narration/story_content%2F5ZIVqtC2X4g_44100_48_0.mp3> a fxs:NarrationTranscript ;
    dcterms:language "en" ;
    schema:duration "PT39S"^^xsd:duration ;
    cnt:chars "Inverter voltage is controlled through reactive current. To understand how the inverter develops the reactive current reference in the dynamics, we can use Kirchhoff's voltage law to calculate the system voltage, VTD1. The equation shows that the active current component of the terminal voltage depends on several terms. Note that the parameter LG which represents the grid inductance and is an indication of the short circuit strength of the grid appears in two of those terms. This suggests that the dynamics of VTD1 depends on grid strength. Click each component of the equation that contributes to system voltage to learn more. Click next to continue." ;
    fxs:transcribedBy <https://github.com/SYSTRAN/faster-whisper#tiny.en> ;
    prov:wasDerivedFrom <https://interego-css.livelysky-8b81abb0.eastus.azurecontainerapps.io/markj/courses/lesson3/asset/story_content%2F5ZIVqtC2X4g_44100_48_0.mp3> .

<https://interego-css.livelysky-8b81abb0.eastus.azurecontainerapps.io/markj/courses/lesson3/asset/story_content%2F6I0VR61PQcO_44100_48_0.mp3> a fxs:Asset ;
    dcterms:format "audio/mpeg" ;
    fxs:fileLocator "package!/story_content/6I0VR61PQcO_44100_48_0.mp3" ;
    schema:duration "PT49S"^^xsd:duration ;
    prov:wasDerivedFrom <https://interego-css.livelysky-8b81abb0.eastus.azurecontainerapps.io/markj/courses/lesson3> .

<https://interego-css.livelysky-8b81abb0.eastus.azurecontainerapps.io/markj/courses/lesson3/narration/story_content%2F6I0VR61PQcO_44100_48_0.mp3> a fxs:NarrationTranscript ;
    dcterms:language "en" ;
    schema:duration "PT49S"^^xsd:duration ;
    cnt:chars "The last term in the equation is system voltage. The presence of the term LG in voltage dynamics makes voltage control dependent on grid strength. The graph shows the step response of the terminal voltage for different grid short circuit ratio or SCR values with the same controller gain. In weaker grid conditions, for example, a short circuit ratio of 2 to 5, the response is faster. However, as the grid gets stronger, for example, a short circuit ratio of 10 to 15, the response slows down because LG is larger and it takes more reactive current to change voltage. In summary, the IBR response is dependent upon both its internal control system and the grid strength at its connection point. The graph of the voltage response at different SCR values is extremely telling." ;
    fxs:transcribedBy <https://github.com/SYSTRAN/faster-whisper#tiny.en> ;
    prov:wasDerivedFrom <https://interego-css.livelysky-8b81abb0.eastus.azurecontainerapps.io/markj/courses/lesson3/asset/story_content%2F6I0VR61PQcO_44100_48_0.mp3> .

<https://interego-css.livelysky-8b81abb0.eastus.azurecontainerapps.io/markj/courses/lesson3/asset/story_content%2F5jMp1uOBvcw_44100_48_0.mp3> a fxs:Asset ;
    dcterms:format "audio/mpeg" ;
    fxs:fileLocator "package!/story_content/5jMp1uOBvcw_44100_48_0.mp3" ;
    schema:duration "PT24S"^^xsd:duration ;
    prov:wasDerivedFrom <https://interego-css.livelysky-8b81abb0.eastus.azurecontainerapps.io/markj/courses/lesson3> .

<https://interego-css.livelysky-8b81abb0.eastus.azurecontainerapps.io/markj/courses/lesson3/narration/story_content%2F5jMp1uOBvcw_44100_48_0.mp3> a fxs:NarrationTranscript ;
    dcterms:language "en" ;
    schema:duration "PT24S"^^xsd:duration ;
    cnt:chars "LG Omega PLLIQ1 represents a voltage across the system inductance due to the rotating reference frame or changing frequency. LG or grid-side inductance can take on a range of values based on system conditions. In a weak grid where LG is large, a small change in reactive current can cause a large change in voltage. This can affect the controller's performance." ;
    fxs:transcribedBy <https://github.com/SYSTRAN/faster-whisper#tiny.en> ;
    prov:wasDerivedFrom <https://interego-css.livelysky-8b81abb0.eastus.azurecontainerapps.io/markj/courses/lesson3/asset/story_content%2F5jMp1uOBvcw_44100_48_0.mp3> .

<https://interego-css.livelysky-8b81abb0.eastus.azurecontainerapps.io/markj/courses/lesson3/asset/story_content%2F6SypeIXvavu_44100_48_0.mp3> a fxs:Asset ;
    dcterms:format "audio/mpeg" ;
    fxs:fileLocator "package!/story_content/6SypeIXvavu_44100_48_0.mp3" ;
    schema:duration "PT24S"^^xsd:duration ;
    prov:wasDerivedFrom <https://interego-css.livelysky-8b81abb0.eastus.azurecontainerapps.io/markj/courses/lesson3> .

<https://interego-css.livelysky-8b81abb0.eastus.azurecontainerapps.io/markj/courses/lesson3/narration/story_content%2F6SypeIXvavu_44100_48_0.mp3> a fxs:NarrationTranscript ;
    dcterms:language "en" ;
    schema:duration "PT24S"^^xsd:duration ;
    cnt:chars "This part of the equation represents the voltage drop due to system inductance and the change rate of the active current. In a weak grid, after a fault, we aim to limit the ramp rate of the active current component, DID1, by DT to avoid rapid changes in ID1 that could lead to undesirable large changes in voltage. LG may take on a range of values based on system conditions." ;
    fxs:transcribedBy <https://github.com/SYSTRAN/faster-whisper#tiny.en> ;
    prov:wasDerivedFrom <https://interego-css.livelysky-8b81abb0.eastus.azurecontainerapps.io/markj/courses/lesson3/asset/story_content%2F6SypeIXvavu_44100_48_0.mp3> .

<https://interego-css.livelysky-8b81abb0.eastus.azurecontainerapps.io/markj/courses/lesson3/asset/story_content%2F5nckAIutyat_44100_48_0.mp3> a fxs:Asset ;
    dcterms:format "audio/mpeg" ;
    fxs:fileLocator "package!/story_content/5nckAIutyat_44100_48_0.mp3" ;
    schema:duration "PT43S"^^xsd:duration ;
    prov:wasDerivedFrom <https://interego-css.livelysky-8b81abb0.eastus.azurecontainerapps.io/markj/courses/lesson3> .

<https://interego-css.livelysky-8b81abb0.eastus.azurecontainerapps.io/markj/courses/lesson3/narration/story_content%2F5nckAIutyat_44100_48_0.mp3> a fxs:NarrationTranscript ;
    dcterms:language "en" ;
    schema:duration "PT43S"^^xsd:duration ;
    cnt:chars "This part of the equation represents voltage drop due to system resistance. Rg is the resistive part of the grid impedance. ID references active power current. In transmission applications, we can assume that the resistive part of grid impedance R is a negligible component of the overall impedance x. Hence, we can ignore Rgid with in voltage dynamics. This suggests that the terminal voltage can be controlled by the reactive current. Looking at the voltage control system, the reference voltage is compared to the measured voltage and the difference is processed by a compensator to develop the reference current. The compensator is typically a proportional integrator controller." ;
    fxs:transcribedBy <https://github.com/SYSTRAN/faster-whisper#tiny.en> ;
    prov:wasDerivedFrom <https://interego-css.livelysky-8b81abb0.eastus.azurecontainerapps.io/markj/courses/lesson3/asset/story_content%2F5nckAIutyat_44100_48_0.mp3> .

<https://interego-css.livelysky-8b81abb0.eastus.azurecontainerapps.io/markj/courses/lesson3/slide/6JZsAHMHpvb> a fxs:Slide ;
    dcterms:title "Fault Ride-Through Response (FRT)" ;
    fxs:identifiedBy "6JZsAHMHpvb" ;
    fxs:sequenceIndex 7 ;
    fxs:fileLocator "package!/html5/data/js/6JZsAHMHpvb.js" ;
    prov:wasDerivedFrom <https://interego-css.livelysky-8b81abb0.eastus.azurecontainerapps.io/markj/courses/lesson3/res/__69JeglEuzyv_RES> ;
    schema:identifier "Slide8" ;
    fxs:embedsAsset <https://interego-css.livelysky-8b81abb0.eastus.azurecontainerapps.io/markj/courses/lesson3/asset/story_content%2F64w1SoQq2BD_44100_48_0.mp3> ;
    fxs:embedsAsset <https://interego-css.livelysky-8b81abb0.eastus.azurecontainerapps.io/markj/courses/lesson3/asset/story_content%2F6O98E7I3oiU_44100_48_0.mp3> ;
    fxs:hasNarration <https://interego-css.livelysky-8b81abb0.eastus.azurecontainerapps.io/markj/courses/lesson3/narration/story_content%2F64w1SoQq2BD_44100_48_0.mp3> ;
    fxs:hasNarration <https://interego-css.livelysky-8b81abb0.eastus.azurecontainerapps.io/markj/courses/lesson3/narration/story_content%2F6O98E7I3oiU_44100_48_0.mp3> ;
    fxs:extractedTextCorpus "Control Objectives; Rectangle 4; Maintain current limits of the power electronics \\nControl dc voltage\\nInject reactive current to keep phase current between 1.1 - 1.5; Rectangle 1; Inject reactive current to support the voltage - either positive or negative sequence; Have fast response time - tens of milliseconds -- based on the agreed code and interconnection requirements; Image 38.emf; Rectangle 2" .

<https://interego-css.livelysky-8b81abb0.eastus.azurecontainerapps.io/markj/courses/lesson3/asset/story_content%2F64w1SoQq2BD_44100_48_0.mp3> a fxs:Asset ;
    dcterms:format "audio/mpeg" ;
    fxs:fileLocator "package!/story_content/64w1SoQq2BD_44100_48_0.mp3" ;
    schema:duration "PT33S"^^xsd:duration ;
    prov:wasDerivedFrom <https://interego-css.livelysky-8b81abb0.eastus.azurecontainerapps.io/markj/courses/lesson3> .

<https://interego-css.livelysky-8b81abb0.eastus.azurecontainerapps.io/markj/courses/lesson3/narration/story_content%2F64w1SoQq2BD_44100_48_0.mp3> a fxs:NarrationTranscript ;
    dcterms:language "en" ;
    schema:duration "PT33S"^^xsd:duration ;
    cnt:chars "So far we've discussed control under normal operating conditions where voltage and frequency are within the normal range and the plant controller generates set points for individual inverters. What do control objectives look like during abnormal conditions such as a fault where the voltage is fallen outside the normal range? When grid voltage is abnormally low or high, the inverter operates in low voltage drive through or high voltage drive through control mode. The plant controls are typically frozen and the inverter control responds to its terminal voltage." ;
    fxs:transcribedBy <https://github.com/SYSTRAN/faster-whisper#tiny.en> ;
    prov:wasDerivedFrom <https://interego-css.livelysky-8b81abb0.eastus.azurecontainerapps.io/markj/courses/lesson3/asset/story_content%2F64w1SoQq2BD_44100_48_0.mp3> .

<https://interego-css.livelysky-8b81abb0.eastus.azurecontainerapps.io/markj/courses/lesson3/asset/story_content%2F6O98E7I3oiU_44100_48_0.mp3> a fxs:Asset ;
    dcterms:format "audio/mpeg" ;
    fxs:fileLocator "package!/story_content/6O98E7I3oiU_44100_48_0.mp3" ;
    schema:duration "PT9S"^^xsd:duration ;
    prov:wasDerivedFrom <https://interego-css.livelysky-8b81abb0.eastus.azurecontainerapps.io/markj/courses/lesson3> .

<https://interego-css.livelysky-8b81abb0.eastus.azurecontainerapps.io/markj/courses/lesson3/narration/story_content%2F6O98E7I3oiU_44100_48_0.mp3> a fxs:NarrationTranscript ;
    dcterms:language "en" ;
    schema:duration "PT9S"^^xsd:duration ;
    cnt:chars "Click on each photo to learn about some control objectives for a fault ride through response. Click next when you have finished to continue to a lesson summary." ;
